		<h4><div>Music musicians<br>love best</div></h4>
		<p>Our musicians love to talk about music! They talk about works they like to hear, which pieces influenced them most, and so on, but what they get passionate about is the music they like to perform themselves. This is the music that makes an MCO Chamber Night special.</p>
		<p>Winds are featured prominently, with a Beethoven octet and several overtures from Mozart operas arranged for those instruments.</p>
		<p>Another program highlight will be Dvo&#345;&aacute;k&rsquo;s A major sextet, with its Slavonic folklore influences. Composed in just two weeks in May of 1878, it was the first work of Dvo&#345;&aacute;k&rsquo;s to be premiered outside of Bohemia.</p>
		<p>For many loyal MCO fans, the newest CD in their collection is likely to be MCO Concertmaster Karl Stobbe&rsquo;s Ysaÿe Sonatas for Solo Violin. How exciting to be able to hear some of it live!
</p>
		<p><b>Stobbe + Ysa&#255;e</b></p>
		<p>MCO Concertmaster Karl Stobbe has just released his Avie Records recording of the six sonatas for solo violin by the late romantic composer and violinist Eug&egrave;ne Ysa&#255;e. Considered some of the most challenging works for solo violin, these extraordinary pieces use every colour and nuance of the violin, from the Spanish flair of the 6th sonata to the exquisite lyricism of the 2nd.</p>
		<p>Anne Manson: &ldquo;The beautiful, lyrical quality of Karl&rsquo;s playing on this exquisite gem of a recording demonstrates once again how lucky we are to have him as Concertmaster of the MCO.&rdquo;</p>

